definition_1: 1. used before countable or singular nouns referring to people or things that have not already been mentioned
definition_2: 2. used to show that somebody/something is a member of a group or profession
definition_3: 3. any, every
definition_4: 4. used before uncountable nouns when these have an adjective in front of them, or phrase following them
definition_5: 5. used in front of two nouns that are seen as a single unit
definition_7: 7. used when talking about prices, quantities and rates
definition_9: 9. used before somebody’s name to show that the speaker does not know the person
definition_10: 10. used before the names of days of the week to talk about one particular day
examples_1:
- a man/horse/unit
- an aunt/egg/hour/X-ray
- I can only carry two at a time.
- There's a visitor for you.
- She's a friend of my father's (= one of my father's friends).
examples_2:
- Their new car's a BMW.
- She's a Buddhist.
- He's a teacher.
- Is that a Monet (= a painting by Monet)?
examples_3: - A lion is a dangerous animal.
examples_4:
- a good knowledge of French
- a sadness that won’t go away
examples_7:
- They cost 50p a kilo.
- I can type 50 words a minute.
- He was driving at 50 miles an hour.
examples_9: - There's a Mrs Green to see you.

definition_1: 1. to leave somebody, especially somebody you are responsible for, with no intention of returning
definition_2: 2. to leave a thing or place, especially because it is impossible or dangerous to stay
definition_3: 3. to stop doing something, especially before it is finished, to stop having something
definition_4: 4. to stop supporting or helping somebody, to stop believing in something
definition_5: 5. to feel an emotion so strongly that you can feel nothing else
examples_1:
-
- People often simply abandon their pets when they go abroad.
-
- The study showed a deep fear among the elderly of being abandoned to the care of strangers.
examples_2:
-
- He gave the order to abandon ship (= to leave the ship because it was sinking).
-
examples_3:
- They abandoned the match because of rain.
- The plans for reform were quietly abandoned.
- She abandoned hope of any reconciliation.
- We had to abandon any further attempt at negotiation.
examples_4:
-
-
- This principle has now been effectively abandoned.

definition_1: 1. the fact that somebody/something is able to do something
definition_2: 2. a level of skill or intelligence
examples_1:
- People with the disease may lose their ability to communicate.
- This program has the ability to adapt to its user.
- Students must demonstrate the ability to understand simple texts.
- She has an uncanny ability to predict what consumers will want.
- A gentle form of exercise will increase your ability to relax.
examples_2:
- Their athletic ability is stunning.
- cognitive/intellectual/mental ability
- A woman of her ability will easily find a job.
- Are you used to teaching students of mixed abilities?
- It's important to discover the natural abilities of each child.
- I try to do my job to the best of my ability (= as well as I can).

definition_1: 1. to have the skill, intelligence, opportunity, etc. needed to do something
definition_2: 2. intelligent, good at something
examples_1:
- You must be able to speak French for this job.
- A viral illness left her barely able to walk.
- We're still able to get visas to come and go from Thailand.
- I didn't feel able to disagree with him.
- Will you be able to come?
- Are you really willing and able to do what is necessary?
- They don't even seem able to see what's good about their ideas.
- These families are less able to afford a balanced, healthy diet.
examples_2:
- She's the ablest student in the class.
- We aim to help the less able in society to lead an independent life.

definition_1: 1. to officially end a law, a system or an institution
examples_1: - This tax should be abolished.

definition_1: 1. the deliberate ending of a
definition_2: 2. a medical operation to end a
definition_3: 3. the process of giving birth to a baby before it is fully developed and able to survive
examples_1:
- to support/oppose abortion
- a woman’s right to abortion
- the country's strict abortion laws
- I've always been anti-abortion.
examples_2:
- She decided to have an abortion.
- Some medical staff wanted the right to refuse to perform abortions.
examples_3: - Higher amounts of caffeine may be associated with increased rates of abortion and low birthweight.

definition_1: 1. a little more or less than, a little before or after
definition_2: 2. nearly, very close to
definition_3: 3. in many directions, here and there
definition_4: 4. in no particular order, in various places
definition_6: 6. able to be found in a place
definition_10: 10. able to go outside again after an illness
definition_12: 12. used to say that you have finished telling somebody about something and there is nothing to add

definition_1: 1. on the subject of somebody/something, in connection with somebody/something
definition_2: 2. used to describe the purpose or an aspect of something
definition_3: 3. busy with something, doing something
definition_4: 4. in many directions in a place, here and there
definition_5: 5. in various parts of a place, here and there
definition_6: 6. next to a place or person, in the area mentioned
definition_8: 8. used when asking for information about somebody/something
examples_1:
- a book about flowers
- Tell me all about it.
- What's she so angry about?
- There's something strange about him.
- There's something about this business that is not quite right.
- I don't know what you're on about (= talking about).
- There's nothing you can do about it now.
examples_2:
- Movies are all about making money these days.
- What was all that about? (= what was the reason for what has just happened?)
examples_3:
- Everywhere people were going about their daily business.
- And while you’re about it… (= while you’re doing that)
examples_4:
- We wandered about the town for an hour or so.
- He looked about the room.
examples_5: - The papers were strewn about the room.
examples_7: - She wore a shawl about her shoulders.
examples_8:
- How about Ruth? Have you heard from her?
- I'm having fish. What about you?
examples_9:
- How about going for a walk?
-
- What about a break?

definition_1: 1. at or to a higher place
definition_2: 2. greater in number, level or age
definition_3: 3. earlier in something written or printed
definition_4: 4. (to do) even more than is expected or demanded
examples_1:
- Put it on the shelf above.
- Seen from above the cars looked tiny.
- I could hear someone calling out my name from up above.
- They were acting on instructions from above (= from somebody in a higher position of authority).
examples_2:
- increases of 5% and above
- A score of 70 or above will get you an ‘A’.
- children aged 12 and above
examples_3:
- As was stated above…
- See above, page 97.
- My client is the mother of the two above-named children.
examples_4: - Our staff members will go above and beyond to ensure that our customers are satisfied.

definition_1: 1. at or to a higher place or position than something/somebody
definition_2: 2. more than something, greater in number, level or age than somebody/something
definition_3: 3. of greater importance or of higher quality than somebody/something
definition_4: 4. too good or too honest to do something
definition_5: 5. louder or clearer than another sound
definition_7: 7. having too high an opinion of yourself

definition_1: 1. in or to a foreign country
definition_2: 2. being talked about or felt by many people
definition_3: 3. outside, outdoors

definition_1: 1. the fact of somebody being away from a place where they are usually expected to be, the occasion or period of time when somebody is away
definition_2: 2. the fact of somebody/something not existing or not being available, a lack of something
definition_3: 3. used to say that when you are away from somebody that you love, you love them even more
definition_4: 4. not present in a situation or place, when it is obvious that you should be there

definition_1: 1. not in a place because of illness, etc.
definition_2: 2. not present in something
definition_3: 3. showing that you are not really looking at or thinking about what is happening around you
examples_1:
- He was absent from work for two weeks.
- Local people were conspicuously absent from the meeting.
examples_2: - Love was totally absent from his childhood.

definition_1: 1. total and complete
definition_2: 2. used, especially in spoken English, to give emphasis to what you are saying
definition_3: 3. definite and without any doubt
definition_6: 6. existing or measured independently and not in relation to something else
examples_1:
- I've joined a class for absolute beginners.
- absolute confidence/trust/silence/truth
- ‘You're wrong,’ she said with absolute certainty.
- Clean water is an absolute necessity.
- Around them the darkness was absolute, the silence oppressive.
examples_2:
- We must keep costs to an absolute minimum.
- This room is an absolute disgrace.
- They're talking absolute nonsense.
- He must earn an absolute fortune.
examples_3:
- There was no absolute proof.
- He taught us that the laws of physics were absolute.
- The story offers no clear message, no absolute truth.
examples_4: - The divorce became absolute last week.
examples_5:
- absolute power/authority
- an absolute ruler/monarchy (= one with no limit to their power)
examples_6:
- Although prices are falling in absolute terms, energy is still expensive.
- Beauty cannot be measured by any absolute standard.

definition_1: 1. used to emphasize that something is completely true
definition_2: 2. used to emphasize something negative
definition_3: 3. used with adjectives or verbs that express strong feelings or extreme qualities to mean ‘extremely’
definition_4: 4. used to emphasize that you agree with somebody, or to give somebody permission to do something
definition_5: 5. used to emphasize that you strongly disagree with somebody, or to refuse permission
definition_6: 6. not considered in relation to other things
examples_1:
- You're absolutely right.
- He made it absolutely clear.
- I'm not absolutely certain I posted it.
- Are you absolutely sure?
- Training is absolutely essential in this business.
- Don't delay for longer than absolutely necessary.
- The place was absolutely packed.
- It was absolutely pouring with rain.
examples_2:
- That man does absolutely no work!
- There's absolutely nothing more the doctors can do.
examples_3:
- absolutely delighted/thrilled
- We were absolutely devastated at the news.
- I absolutely love strawberries.
- She absolutely adores you.
- absolutely fantastic/amazing
- He's an absolutely brilliant cook.
examples_4:
- ‘They could have told us, couldn't they?’ ‘Absolutely!’
- ‘Can we leave a little early?’ ‘Absolutely!’
examples_5:
- ‘Was it any good?’ ‘No, absolutely not.’
- ‘Can I stay up late?’ ‘Absolutely not!’
examples_6: - White-collar crime increased both absolutely and in comparison with other categories.

definition_1: 1. to take in a liquid, gas or other substance from the surface or space around
definition_2: 2. to take in and keep heat, light, energy, sound, etc. instead of reflecting it
definition_3: 3. to reduce the effect of a physical impact or movement
definition_4: 4. to take something into the mind and learn or understand it
definition_5: 5. to interest somebody very much so that they pay no attention to anything else
definition_6: 6. to make something smaller become part of something larger
definition_7: 7. to use up a large supply of something, especially money or time
definition_8: 8. to deal with changes, effects, costs, etc.
examples_1:
-
- Let the rice cook until it has absorbed all the water.
-
examples_2: - Black walls absorb a lot of heat during the day.
examples_3:
- This tennis racket absorbs shock on impact.
- The bats have graphite shafts that absorb the vibration.
examples_4:
- It's a lot of information to absorb all at once.
- It took me several days to absorb the fact of her death.
- They spent a week in Paris just absorbing the atmosphere.
examples_5:
- This work had absorbed him for several years.
- His work absorbed him completely.
examples_6:
-
-
- These committees were gradually absorbed into the local government machine.
examples_7:
- The new proposals would absorb $80 billion of the federal budget.
- My work absorbs a great deal of my time.
examples_8: - The company is unable to absorb such huge losses.

definition_1: 1. based on general ideas and not on any particular real person, thing or situation
definition_2: 2. existing in thought or as an idea but not having a physical reality
definition_3: 3. not representing people or things in a realistic way, but expressing the artist’s ideas about them
examples_1:
- abstract knowledge/principles
- The research shows that pre-school children are capable of thinking in abstract terms.
examples_2: - We may talk of beautiful things but beauty itself is abstract.
examples_3: - the work of American abstract expressionists like Mark Rothko

definition_1: 1. extremely silly, not logical and sensible
definition_2: 2. things that are or that seem to be
examples_1:
- That uniform makes the guards look absurd.
- Of course it's not true, what an absurd idea.
examples_2: - He has a good sense of the absurd.

definition_1: 1. a large quantity that is more than enough
definition_2: 2. in large quantities
examples_1:
- The brochure promised beautiful walks with an abundance of wildlife.
- The country has an abundance of natural resources.
- We were amazed by the sheer abundance of food.
examples_2:
- Fruit and vegetables grew in abundance on the island.
- Exotic plants grew there in great abundance.

definition_1: 1. the use of something in a way that is wrong or harmful
definition_2: 2. unfair, cruel or violent treatment of somebody
definition_3: 3. rude and offensive remarks, usually made when somebody is very angry
examples_1:
- alcohol/drug abuse
- The system of paying cash bonuses is open to abuse (= might be used in the wrong way).
- The legal system is open to abuse.
-
- What she did was an abuse of her position as manager.
examples_2:
- child abuse
- sexual abuse
- reported abuses by the secret police
- She suffered years of physical abuse.
examples_3:
- to scream/hurl/shout abuse
- a stream/torrent of abuse
- The man burst into a torrent of foul-mouthed racist abuse.

definition_1: 1. connected with education, especially studying in schools and universities
definition_2: 2. involving a lot of reading and studying rather than practical or technical skills
definition_3: 3. good at subjects involving a lot of reading and studying
definition_4: 4. not connected to a real or practical situation and therefore not important
examples_1:
- high/low academic standards
- She had a brilliant academic career.
- one of this country's most prestigious academic institutions
- improving the academic achievement of all students
- The university is renowned throughout the world for its academic excellence.
- academic research/researchers
- We are deeply committed to safeguarding academic freedom.
examples_2:
- a mixture of vocational and academic courses
- people whose skills are practical rather than academic
- academic qualifications/subjects
examples_3: - She wasn't very academic and hated school.
examples_4:
- It's a purely academic question.
- The whole thing's academic now—we can't win anyway.
- Most of his questions were of an academic nature.

definition_1: 1. a person who teaches and/or does research at a university or college
examples_1:
- a leading/distinguished/prominent academic
- There is much debate among academics about this issue.

definition_1: 1. a school or college for special training
definition_2: 2. a type of official organization that aims to encourage and develop art, literature, science, etc.
definition_4: 4. a private school in the US
definition_5: 5. a school in England that is independent of local authority control

definition_1: 1. to happen faster or earlier, to make something happen faster or earlier
definition_2: 2. to start to go faster
examples_1:
- Inflation continues to accelerate.
-
examples_2:
- The runners accelerated smoothly around the bend.
- The car accelerated to overtake me.
- The car purred into life and accelerated away.

definition_1: 1. a way of pronouncing the words of a language that shows which country, area or social class a person comes from, how well somebody pronounces a particular language
definition_2: 2. the emphasis that you should give to part of a word when saying it
definition_3: 3. a mark on a letter to show that it should be pronounced in a particular way
definition_4: 4. a special importance that is given to something
examples_1:
- a northern/Dublin/Scottish accent
- a strong/broad accent (= one that is easy to notice)
-
- The Americans had learned Korean and spoke with a good accent.
examples_2: - In ‘today’ the accent is on the second syllable.
examples_3: - Canapé has an accent on the ‘e’.
examples_4: - In all our products the accent is on quality.

definition_1: 1. to take willingly something that is offered, to say ‘yes’ to an offer, invitation, etc.
definition_2: 2. to agree to or approve of something
definition_3: 3. to take payment in a particular form
definition_4: 4. to admit that you are responsible or to blame for something
definition_5: 5. to continue in a difficult situation without complaining, because you realize that you cannot change it
definition_6: 6. to make somebody feel welcome and part of a group
definition_7: 7. to believe that something is true
definition_8: 8. to allow somebody to join an organization, attend an institution, use a service, etc.
examples_1:
- He asked me to marry him and I accepted.
-
- It was pouring with rain so I accepted his offer of a lift.
- I am unfortunately unable to accept your kind invitation.
- The board of directors accepted our proposal.
- She's decided not to accept the job.
- Please accept this small token of my appreciation.
-
-
examples_2:
-
- The judge refused to accept his evidence.
- He accepted all the changes we proposed.
- Are you willing to accept the challenge?
-
-
examples_3:
- This machine only accepts coins.
- Credit cards are widely accepted.
examples_4:
- He accepts full responsibility for what happened.
- You have to accept the consequences of your actions.
examples_5:
-
- to be willing/prepared to accept something
- Nothing will change as long as the workers continue to accept these appalling conditions.
-
-
examples_7:
-
-
-
- I am not prepared to accept that this decision is final.
-
- something is accepted to be, have, etc. something

definition_1: 1. agreed or approved of by most people in a society
definition_2: 2. that somebody agrees is of a good enough standard or allowed
definition_3: 3. not very good but good enough
examples_1:
- Children must learn socially acceptable behaviour.
- It is perfectly acceptable for you as an employee to say no.
examples_2:
- For this course a pass in English at grade B is acceptable.
- Air pollution in the city had reached four times the acceptable levels.
-
- It is possible to find a solution that is acceptable to both sides.
examples_3:
- The food was acceptable, but no more.
- Inspectors found that teaching standards were acceptable, but could be improved.

definition_1: 1. the act of accepting a gift, an invitation, an offer, etc.
definition_2: 2. the act of agreeing with something and approving of it
definition_3: 3. the process of allowing somebody to join something or be a member of a group
definition_4: 4. the quality of being willing to accept an unpleasant or difficult situation
examples_1:
- Please confirm your acceptance of this offer in writing.
- He made a short acceptance speech/speech of acceptance.
- Invitations have been sent out and 80 acceptances have already been received.
- So far we have had one refusal and three acceptances.
examples_2: - The new laws have gained widespread acceptance.
examples_3:
- Your acceptance into the insurance plan is guaranteed.
- Social acceptance is important for most young people.
- The group is now seeking formal acceptance.

definition_1: 1. the opportunity or right to use something or to see somebody/something
definition_2: 2. a way of entering or reaching a place
examples_1:
- High-speed internet access has become a necessity.
-
- access to information/services/resources
- access to healthcare/education
- They are seeking increased access to markets overseas.
- to provide/allow access to something/somebody
- to restrict/block access to something/somebody
- Journalists were denied access to the President.
- Many divorced fathers only have access to their children at weekends (= they are allowed by law to see them only at weekends).
examples_2:
- The police gained access through a broken window.
- Many paths have become overgrown, blocking access.
- There is easy access by road.
-
- The only access to the farmhouse is across the fields.

definition_1: 1. to open a computer file or use a computer system
definition_2: 2. to be able to have or use something, especially something that you have a right to
definition_3: 3. to reach, enter or use something
examples_1:
- Most people use their phones to access the internet.
- to access a file/database
- It has never been easier to access information.
- All employees can access real-time data.
- You should regularly change the password you use to access your online accounts.
-
examples_2:
- Being informed is the first step toward accessing better health services.
- States need to understand how to access the federal resources that are available.
- Businesses often provide their products at a discount in order to access a potential market.
examples_3:
-
- The balcony is accessed via French doors from the living room.

definition_1: 1. that can be reached, entered, used, seen, etc.
definition_2: 2. that can be reached, entered, used, etc. by somebody who has problems walking
definition_3: 3. easy to understand
definition_4: 4. easy to talk to and to get to know

definition_1: 1. an unpleasant event, especially in a vehicle, that happens unexpectedly and causes injury or damage
definition_2: 2. something that happens unexpectedly and is not planned in advance
definition_3: 3. a thing or person that is very likely to cause danger or a problem in the future because of the condition it is in or the way they behave
definition_5: 5. in a way that is not planned or organized
definition_6: 6. a series of unpleasant events caused by bad luck

definition_1: 1. by chance, in a way that was not planned
examples_1:
- As I turned around, I accidentally hit him in the face.
- The damage couldn't have been caused accidentally.

definition_1: 1. to provide somebody with a room or place to sleep, live or sit
definition_2: 2. to provide enough space for somebody/something
definition_3: 3. to consider something such as somebody’s opinion or a fact and be influenced by it when you are deciding what to do or explaining something
definition_4: 4. to help somebody by doing what they want
definition_5: 5. to change your behaviour so that you can deal with a new situation better
examples_1:
- The hotel can accommodate up to 500 guests.
- The aircraft is capable of accommodating 28 passengers.
examples_2:
- The garage can accommodate three cars.
- The old town hall now accommodates a Folk Museum.
examples_3:
- Our proposal tries to accommodate the special needs of minority groups.
- She modified her views so as to accommodate the objections of American feminists.
examples_4:
- I have accommodated the press a great deal, giving numerous interviews.
- I’m sure the bank will be able to accommodate you.
examples_5: - I needed to accommodate to the new schedule.

definition_1: 1. to succeed in doing or completing something
examples_1:
- The first part of the plan has been safely accomplished.
- I don't feel I've accomplished very much today.
- That's it. Mission accomplished (= we have done what we aimed to do).
